\f0\fs24 \cf0 # myaircraft.us \'97 Historical Aircraft Logbook Structuring + High-Accuracy Extraction\
## Additional Build Instructions for Codex\
\
You are enhancing **myaircraft.us**, an AI-powered aircraft records, maintenance, and compliance platform.\
\
This update is specifically for the **historical aircraft logbook ingestion, organization, extraction, and retrieval system**.\
\
The goal is to make old physical aircraft logbooks usable, searchable, structured, and highly reliable at scale.\
\
---\
\
# Core Idea\
\
Aircraft owners and operators may have many **physical maintenance logbooks** for one aircraft.\
\
These books must be:\
\
1. **Scanned and digitized**\
2. **Organized by logbook/book number**\
3. **Returned physically in an organized way**\
4. **Parsed with very high accuracy**\
5. **Converted into structured maintenance records**\
6. **Stored in a robust RAG + database architecture**\
7. **Made searchable through one intelligent interface**\
\
---\
\
# Critical Business Logic\
\
## 1. Historical records must be organized by BOOK, not by year\
\
For old/historical aircraft records:\
\
- Do **not** organize primarily by year\
- Organize by **Logbook Number**\
- Example:\
  - Aircraft Logbook #1\
  - Aircraft Logbook #2\
  - Aircraft Logbook #3\
  - Engine Logbook #1\
  - Propeller Logbook #1\
\
Each physical book should have a clear identity in the system.\
\
### Required workflow:\
- When a physical logbook is received, assign it a label/sticker:\
  - `"MyAircraft Logbook Number 1"`\
  - `"MyAircraft Logbook Number 2"`\
  - etc.\
- This label must exist both:\
  - in the physical workflow\
  - in the digital platform\
\
This ensures:\
- clean return-to-owner process\
- clean chain of custody\
- clear digital-to-physical mapping\
\
---\
\
## 2. Going forward, future records can be organized year by year\
\
Historical backfill = organized by **book**\
\
Future workflow = may additionally support:\
- yearly grouping\
- monthly grouping\
- digitally submitted entries\
- scanned single entries\
- direct mechanic uploads\
\
But legacy data must first respect **book structure**\
\
---\
\
# High-Accuracy Extraction Requirement\
\
This is NOT basic OCR.\
\
This system must be designed for **extremely careful extraction**, because small mistakes can create compliance, maintenance, and legal problems.\
\
Examples of sensitive fields:\
- tail number\
- registration number\
- dates\
- tach time\
- Hobbs time\
- total time\
- engine time\
- serial numbers\
- part numbers\
- AD references\
- mechanic certificate / A&P / IA numbers\
- inspection type\
- signatures\
- return to service statements\
\
Accuracy is mission-critical.\
\
---\
\
# Required Structured Data Per Entry\
\
For each extracted maintenance entry, at minimum extract:\
\
1. **Aircraft Tail Number**\
2. **Entry Date**\
3. **Context / Entry Type**\
4. **Body / Full Maintenance Narrative**\
5. **Signer Information**\
\
### Expand \'93Context / Entry Type\'94 into structured categories such as:\
- 100-hour inspection\
- annual inspection\
- preventive maintenance\
- oil change\
- AD compliance\
- repairs\
- alterations\
- component replacement\
- engine work\
- propeller work\
- avionics work\
- discrepancy correction\
- return to service\
- unknown / uncategorized\
\
### Expand \'93Signer Information\'94 into subfields:\
- mechanic name\
- certificate number\
- role/type if identifiable:\
  - A&P\
  - IA\
  - Repair Station\
  - Pilot/Owner\
  - Inspector\
- signature presence flag\
- signature image crop if available\
\
---\
\
# Additional Structured Metadata Required\
\
For every document, page, and entry, preserve layered structure:\
\
## A. Aircraft Level\
- aircraft id\
- tail number\
- make\
- model\
- serial number\
- registration info\
- linked registry profile\
\
## B. Book Level\
- book id\
- book number\
- book type:\
  - airframe\
  - engine\
  - propeller\
  - appliance\
  - avionics\
  - miscellaneous\
- historical or current flag\
- date range covered if known\
- page count\
- physical label id\
- scan batch id\
\
## C. Page Level\
- page id\
- source book id\
- page number within book\
- scanned image\
- OCR text\
- confidence score\
- handwriting detection flag\
- review required flag\
\
## D. Entry Level\
- entry id\
- source page id\
- aircraft id\
- book id\
- entry date\
- entry type/context\
- extracted body text\
- signer name\
- signer certificate number\
- compliance references\
- times / hours fields\
- parts mentioned\
- manual review status\
- confidence score\
- final approved flag\
\
---\
\
# Ingestion Workflow\
\
Build a structured ingestion pipeline:\
\
## Step 1 \'97 Intake\
- user creates or selects aircraft\
- user uploads scanned files or image batches\
- system asks:\
  - what type of logbook is this?\
  - what book number is this?\
  - is this historical or ongoing?\
- allow staff/admin to override and correct\
\
## Step 2 \'97 Book Assignment\
Every uploaded file batch must be assigned to:\
- aircraft\
- book type\
- book number\
\
Example:\
- N123AB\
- Airframe Logbook\
- Book 4\
\
## Step 3 \'97 Scan Quality Validation\
Before extraction:\
- detect blur\
- detect skew\
- detect cut-off pages\
- detect low contrast\
- detect rotated pages\
- detect duplicate pages\
- flag unreadable pages\
\
If scan quality is weak:\
- mark page for rescan\
- do not silently trust extraction\
\
## Step 4 \'97 OCR + Handwriting Extraction\
Use a pipeline designed for:\
- printed text\
- handwritten entries\
- stamps\
- signatures\
- mixed-layout aviation maintenance records\
\
Do not treat all pages the same.\
Use document-type-aware extraction.\
\
## Step 5 \'97 Entry Segmentation\
A page may contain:\
- one maintenance entry\
- multiple entries\
- continuation text from previous page\
- stamps and signatures\
- marginal notes\
\
The system must segment entries intelligently.\
\
## Step 6 \'97 Structured Extraction\
Convert each entry into database fields.\
\
## Step 7 \'97 Confidence Scoring\
Each extracted field gets a confidence score.\
Low-confidence fields must be flagged.\
\
## Step 8 \'97 Human Review Layer\
Historical records require review tools for:\
- correcting dates\
- correcting tail numbers\
- correcting signer names\
- correcting certificate numbers\
- correcting times\
- merging split entries\
- splitting merged entries\
\
## Step 9 \'97 Final Approval\
Only approved extracted entries become \'93trusted structured records\'94.\
\
---\
\
# Review and Validation UX\
\
Build a dedicated admin/reviewer interface for historical logbooks.\
\
## Reviewer must be able to:\
- view original scan beside extracted text\
- edit structured fields\
- approve page\
- approve entry\
- reject extraction\
- request rescan\
- merge pages\
- split entries\
- tag uncertain fields\
- compare OCR output with final reviewed version\
\
## Confidence-based highlighting:\
- red = low confidence\
- yellow = medium confidence\
- green = high confidence\
\
## Special validation warnings:\
- invalid date formats\
- impossible time jumps\
- tail number mismatch\
- signer mismatch\
- duplicate entry suspicion\
- missing signature\
- certificate number pattern issue\
- inspection wording incomplete\
\
---\
\
# Mechanic / Signer Intelligence Layer\
\
The system should build historical signer intelligence over time.\
\
If 100+ mechanics signed across years, the platform should allow:\
\
- searching by signer name\
- grouping entries by signer\
- showing timeline of when each mechanic signed\
- linking variations of the same name\
- linking certificate numbers\
- flagging possible duplicate identities\
\
Example:\
- \'93Show all annual inspections signed by John Doe\'94\
- \'93Show entries signed by this IA from 2018\'962024\'94\
- \'93Find every 100-hour inspection across all books for this aircraft\'94\
\
This should become one of the strongest search features.\
\
---\
\
# Search / RAG Requirements\
\
The RAG system must be **solid**, not generic/basic.\
\
## Must support:\
- semantic search\
- exact keyword search\
- filtered search\
- structured lookup\
- book-level search\
- page-level search\
- entry-level search\
\
## Example queries:\
- \'93Show me the last 100-hour inspection\'94\
- \'93Who signed the annual in 2021?\'94\
- \'93Find all entries mentioning cylinder #3\'94\
- \'93Find all AD compliance references\'94\
- \'93Show every oil change in Book 2\'94\
- \'93Find entries signed by this mechanic\'94\
- \'93Show all maintenance between Jan 2020 and Dec 2021\'94\
- \'93Find entries mentioning magneto replacement\'94\
- \'93Which book contains the first overhaul reference?\'94\
\
## Important:\
Do not rely only on embeddings.\
Use a hybrid system:\
- structured database filters\
- full-text indexing\
- embeddings / semantic retrieval\
- metadata filters\
- confidence / trust ranking\
\
---\
\
# Scale Expectations\
\
Design the architecture to support large historical loads.\
\
Approximate scale:\
- one aircraft may have **5,000 to 7,000 pages**\
- some customers may have **100+ aircraft**\
- system must handle hundreds of thousands of pages across accounts\
\
This means:\
- async-safe ingestion pipeline\
- resumable processing jobs\
- page batching\
- queue-based extraction\
- idempotent processing\
- deduplication\
- incremental reprocessing\
\
---\
\
# Data Model Priorities\
\
Use a database design that separates:\
\
- raw upload files\
- scan batches\
- books\
- pages\
- entries\
- signers\
- extracted entities\
- review events\
- audit logs\
\
## Keep both:\
1. raw source truth\
2. reviewed structured truth\
\
Never overwrite original extracted output without audit history.\
\
---\
\
